"""
MKT Christ — 2 Samuel chapters 1–3
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-2samuel-1-3-full.py

Ch1: David receives Saul's death news; executes the Amalekite; the qinah lament (27 verses)
Ch2: David anointed at Hebron; Ishbosheth installed; pool of Gibeon civil war (32 verses)
Ch3: Civil war; Abner defects; Michal returned; Joab murders Abner; David's lament (39 verses)

Key Christological themes:
- The anointed's inviolability (1:14) — fulfilled in Christ as the supreme Mashiach
- Crown and regalia transferred through death to the rightful heir (Phil 2:9-11)
- Jonathan's surpassing covenant love (1:26) → John 15:13 (greater love)
- The qinah lament as type of Christ mourning the fallen (John 11:35; Luke 19:41)
- Two-stage anointing (Judah first, then all Israel) → gospel to Jew first, then Gentile
- David's inquiry of YHWH before acting → Christ's constant orientation to the Father
- Jabesh-gilead outreach → Christ seeking those who show covenant faithfulness
- Asahel's zeal without wisdom vs. Christ's perfect union of zeal and wisdom
- David growing stronger, Saul's house weaker → Christ's kingdom advancing over the old order
- Abner's oath fulfilling what YHWH swore → 2 Cor 1:20 (all promises find Yes in Christ)
- Michal reclaimed as bride → Christ reclaiming his church (Eph 5:25-27)
- David innocent of Abner's blood (3:28) → Christ's complete righteousness
- David's kenotic weakness before sons of Zeruiah (3:39) → Phil 2:7-8
- Committing judgment to YHWH (3:39) → Christ entrusting judgment to the Father (1 Pet 2:23)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRIST = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>David at Ziklag after defeating the Amalekites — positioned on the frontier, waiting for news of the kingdom. The returning warrior-king who waits for the news that will initiate his reign is a type of Christ, who after his resurrection ascends to the Father and waits (Heb 10:12-13: &#8220;he sat down at the right hand of God, waiting from that time until his enemies should be made a footstool for his feet&#8221;). David&#8217;s two days at Ziklag after his victory is the gap before the announcement that changes everything — as the three days of the tomb precede the resurrection announcement.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The messenger arrives with torn clothes and earth on his head — the visual communication of national disaster. The bringing of news of catastrophic loss to the anointed king is the type of every messenger who must report death to the one who will ultimately answer it. Christ is the one who receives the news of all human death and loss — not as a bystander but as the one who has authority to answer it. John 11:33-35: when Jesus heard that Lazarus was dead and saw Mary weeping, &#8220;he was deeply moved in his spirit and greatly troubled&#8221; and wept — the king who receives the news of death is moved to respond with resurrection.</p>",
    "3": "<p>David&#8217;s first question: &#8220;Where have you come from?&#8221; — establishing the messenger&#8217;s origin before receiving his report. The discernment of the source of a message — its origin, authority, and reliability — is itself a Christological theme. Christ distinguishes between what comes from the Father and what does not (John 8:42-47); he tests the spirits and knows who speaks truth. The messengers who come to the anointed are evaluated by their origin and content. The Amalekite&#8217;s true origin — an opportunist from the enemy camp — disqualifies his report even before its content is assessed.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The catastrophe report: troops fled, many fell, Saul and Jonathan dead. The news of simultaneous military defeat and royal death is the worst possible report — the covenant army broken, the anointed king fallen, the crown prince killed. The typological resonance with the crucifixion is precise: at Calvary, the disciples fled (Matt 26:56), the people watched (Luke 23:35), and the king was dead. The disciples on the road to Emmaus embody the post-Golgotha despair: &#8220;we had hoped that he was the one to redeem Israel&#8221; (Luke 24:21). The death of the anointed seems to end the story.</p>",
    "5": "<p>David&#8217;s focus on Saul and Jonathan specifically — not merely on the battle outcome — reveals the relational priority of the anointed king. Christ&#8217;s resurrection interest is similarly personal: he asks Mary &#8220;whom are you seeking?&#8221; (John 20:15), sends the disciples to &#8220;my brothers&#8221; (Matt 28:10), and asks Peter personally &#8220;do you love me?&#8221; (John 21:17). The risen king&#8217;s first concern is not the geopolitical consequences but the specific persons — particularly those in covenant relationship with him. David&#8217;s &#8220;how do you know?&#8221; is the demand for personal testimony rather than hearsay.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Amalekite claims to have been present on Mount Gilboa at the moment of Saul&#8217;s death. Whether his account is true or embellished, he presents himself as the witness to the anointed&#8217;s last moments and the bearer of his regalia. The false witness who claims authority over the anointed&#8217;s death recurs in the passion narrative: those who came to arrest Jesus claimed authority over him (John 18:12), those who tried him claimed to execute YHWH&#8217;s justice (John 19:7). In every case the false claim to authority over the anointed is overturned — the Amalekite by David&#8217;s sword, Christ&#8217;s captors by the resurrection.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Saul calls to the Amalekite: &#8220;Who are you?&#8221; — the dying king&#8217;s question. The question of identity is the Christological question par excellence: &#8220;Who do you say that I am?&#8221; (Matt 16:15). Saul&#8217;s use of <em>hinnēnî</em> (here I am) by the Amalekite is the covenant-availability formula debased — used not in covenantal faithfulness but in opportunism. Christ&#8217;s <em>hinnēnî</em> in Heb 2:13 (quoting Isa 8:18: &#8220;here I am and the children God has given me&#8221;) is the true and perfect use of the formula — the Son presenting himself and his redeemed household to the Father.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Amalekite&#8217;s self-identification: &#8220;I am an Amalekite.&#8221; The irony is that Amalek — the paradigmatic enemy of Israel from Exod 17 — is the one claiming credit for executing the king whom YHWH had rejected for his failure to destroy Amalek. YHWH&#8217;s judgment has an inexorable quality: what Saul refused to do, YHWH accomplished through the very agent Saul spared. The principle that human disobedience does not ultimately frustrate divine justice but is incorporated into its execution finds its most complete expression in the cross: &#8220;this Jesus, delivered up according to the definite plan and foreknowledge of God, you crucified and killed by the hands of lawless men&#8221; (Acts 2:23).</p>",
    "9": "<p>Saul&#8217;s request for death — &#8220;Stand over me and kill me, for anguish has seized me, yet my life still lingers&#8221; — is the failed king&#8217;s desire to die with some control over his manner of death. The contrast with Christ is total: Christ did not seek death but accepted it as the Father&#8217;s will (Luke 22:42: &#8220;not my will but yours be done&#8221;). Saul&#8217;s death is a flight from shame; Christ&#8217;s is a willing self-offering for redemption. Saul dies because his mission failed; Christ dies because his mission is accomplished (John 19:30: &#8220;it is finished&#8221;).</p>",
    "10": "<p>The taking of the royal regalia — the <em>nezer</em> (crown) and <em>ʾeṣʿāḏāh</em> (armband) — from the fallen king and their presentation to David is the type of Christ receiving the kingdom through his death. The Amalekite thinks he is doing David a favor by bringing the regalia; in fact he has enacted the principle Paul articulates in Phil 2:9-11: &#8220;God has highly exalted him and bestowed on him the name that is above every name&#8221; — the exaltation of Christ follows and is consequent on his humiliation. The crown passes from the fallen king to the rightful heir not despite the death but through it.</p>",
    "11": "<p>David and his men tear their clothes — the immediate mourning response to the news of Saul and Jonathan&#8217;s death. The anointed king mourning over the fallen is the pattern Christ fulfills in John 11:33-35 (weeping at Lazarus&#8217;s tomb) and Luke 19:41 (weeping over Jerusalem). The communal mourning — David and all his men together — anticipates the communal grief of the disciples after the crucifixion (Luke 24:17: they walked &#8220;looking sad&#8221;). In both cases the mourning of the anointed and his people precedes the reversal that only the anointed can bring.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The fast until evening for Saul, Jonathan, &#8220;the people of YHWH&#8221;, and &#8220;the house of Israel&#8221; — David mourns not just two individuals but the covenant people as a whole. Christ&#8217;s intercessory grief encompasses not individuals only but the whole community of those who bear his Father&#8217;s name: &#8220;Holy Father, keep them in your name&#8221; (John 17:11). The anointed king&#8217;s grief is covenant-shaped, extending to all who belong to the covenant community. David fasts for those who were his enemies as well as his covenant-brother Jonathan — Christ prays for those who crucify him (Luke 23:34).</p>",
    "13": "<p>David&#8217;s juridical inquiry — &#8220;Where are you from?&#8221; — establishes the Amalekite&#8217;s identity as a <em>ger</em> (resident alien) under Israelite jurisdiction. The legal accountability of everyone before the anointed king is the type of the universal judgment before Christ: &#8220;we must all appear before the judgment seat of Christ&#8221; (2 Cor 5:10). No one is outside the jurisdiction of the anointed&#8217;s judgment; the resident alien is as accountable as the native-born. The Amalekite&#8217;s claim to have acted beneficially (bringing news, carrying regalia) does not excuse his violation of the anointed&#8217;s inviolability.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&#8220;How were you not afraid to stretch out your hand to destroy YHWH&#8217;s anointed?&#8221; David&#8217;s charge establishes the theological axiom: the <em>māšîaḥ YHWH</em> is inviolable to human violence. The charge is supremely ironic when applied to the passion: those who condemned and crucified Christ violated this axiom in its ultimate form. Yet the difference is decisive — Saul&#8217;s anointing was conditional and had been formally revoked (1 Sam 15:23, 26); Christ&#8217;s anointing is eternal and unconditional (Ps 2:7; Heb 1:5). The violation of the anointed is an act of cosmic transgression whose full reckoning belongs to the judgment of God.</p>",
    "15": "<p>David orders the messenger&#8217;s execution: &#8220;Go, strike him down.&#8221; The immediate execution of the one who claims to have killed the anointed is the judicial principle that the anointed&#8217;s death requires accounting. The cross requires accounting — and the NT&#8217;s proclamation is that the accounting has been made, both in the cross itself (where Christ bears the sin of those who crucify him) and in the coming judgment (where all who rejected the anointed face the consequences). David&#8217;s sword against the false messiah-killer is the type of the eschatological judgment against all who exalted themselves over Christ.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&#8220;Your blood is on your own head, for your mouth testified against you.&#8221; The self-incrimination principle — that one&#8217;s own words establish culpability — is applied at the judgment of the anointed. Jesus warned: &#8220;by your words you will be justified, and by your words you will be condemned&#8221; (Matt 12:37). The Amalekite&#8217;s boast about killing the anointed is his condemnation; those who boasted at the cross — &#8220;his blood be on us and on our children&#8221; (Matt 27:25) — accepted precisely this self-incriminating formula. The blood-guilt returns on those who claim responsibility for the anointed&#8217;s death.</p>",
    "17": "<p>David composes a lament (<em>qînāh</em>) over Saul and Jonathan. The anointed king who mourns the fallen with a formal, teachable lament is the type of Christ who laments and commemorates those who have died. The author of Hebrews applies Ps 22 (David&#8217;s lament-psalm) to Christ on the cross; the church&#8217;s mourning liturgy (lament psalms, Good Friday liturgy) is the continuation of the anointed&#8217;s grief over the fallen. The royal lament poet who creates a form for communal mourning is the forerunner of Christ who himself becomes the content of the church&#8217;s lament and hope.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The instruction that the lament be taught to the sons of Judah, written in the Book of Jashar — the commanded transmission of grief and honor for the fallen. The catechetical function of the lament: not merely expressing personal grief but shaping communal memory. Christ commands his disciples to &#8220;do this in remembrance of me&#8221; (Luke 22:19) — the Eucharist is the commanded transmission of the lament and triumph of the anointed, given to the community to perform until he returns. Teaching the lament is itself a covenant act.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&#8220;Your glory, O Israel, lies slain on your high places! How the mighty have fallen!&#8221; — the opening cry of the dirge. Applied proleptically to Christ: the glory of Israel (John 1:14: &#8220;we beheld his glory, glory as of the only Son from the Father&#8221;) lies slain at Golgotha — also a high place outside Jerusalem. The crucifixion is the ultimate &#8220;how the mighty have fallen&#8221; moment in redemptive history — the Son of God in whom all the fullness of deity dwells (Col 2:9) is slain. But the lament does not end the story; the resurrection is the answer to the qinah.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&#8220;Tell it not in Gath, proclaim it not in the streets of Ashkelon, lest the daughters of the Philistines rejoice.&#8221; The silencing of the enemy&#8217;s celebration is the anti-shame motif. At the crucifixion, the powers of darkness celebrate (Col 2:15: Christ&#8217;s death appeared to be their triumph). But Paul&#8217;s proclamation reverses the logic: Christ at the cross &#8220;disarmed the rulers and authorities and put them to open shame, by triumphing over them in it&#8221; — what appeared to be the enemy&#8217;s celebration was their defeat. The resurrection is the ultimate &#8220;tell it not in Gath&#8221; reversal: the apparent occasion for the enemy&#8217;s rejoicing becomes their exposure.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The curse on Gilboa — no dew, no rain, no firstfruits — and the image of Saul&#8217;s unoiled shield: the battlefield is cursed because the anointed died there. The place of the anointed&#8217;s death is not irrelevant geography but covenantally significant ground. Golgotha is similarly charged: the skull-place becomes the site of the new creation&#8217;s inauguration. The unoiled shield — abandoned, decaying — is the image of protection withdrawn; Christ&#8217;s death appears to be the withdrawal of all protection and blessing. But the resurrection vindicates the place: the tomb becomes the site of triumph, the cross the tree of life.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The heroic epitaph: Jonathan&#8217;s bow and Saul&#8217;s sword never turned back from the blood of the slain. The warrior&#8217;s weapons that always reached their target are the type of Christ&#8217;s mission that never fails. Isa 55:11: &#8220;my word that goes out from my mouth shall not return to me empty, but it shall accomplish that which I purpose, and shall succeed in the thing for which I sent it.&#8221; The divine weapon — the word of the cross — always reaches its target. Christ&#8217;s mission of redemption never turns back; the bow of his covenant purpose never misses.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Saul and Jonathan — beloved and lovely, swifter than eagles, stronger than lions, inseparable in life and death. The lament idealizes the fallen warriors beyond their historical complexity. The NT&#8217;s proclamation of Christ goes beyond idealization to ontological truth: &#8220;he is the image of the invisible God, the firstborn over all creation&#8221; (Col 1:15); &#8220;in him the whole fullness of deity dwells bodily&#8221; (Col 2:9). The heroic praise that the lament-genre reaches for in honoring warriors finds its only fully adequate referent in Christ — the one who is genuinely all that heroic poetry claims its subjects to be.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&#8220;O daughters of Israel, weep for Saul, who clothed you in scarlet with luxuries, who put gold ornaments on your clothing.&#8221; The king who enriched his people through his victories is mourned by those who benefited from his rule. Christ is the king who clothes his people not with the material spoil of battle but with his own righteousness: &#8220;I counsel you to buy from me gold refined by fire, and white garments so that you may clothe yourself and the shame of your nakedness may not be seen&#8221; (Rev 3:18). The daughters of Israel weeping for Saul&#8217;s material gifts are the type of the bride of Christ clothed in &#8220;fine linen, bright and pure&#8221; (Rev 19:8).</p>",
    "25": "<p>&#8220;How the mighty have fallen in the midst of battle! Jonathan lies slain on your high places.&#8221; The second sounding of the refrain focuses on Jonathan — the covenant-friend who died in the king&#8217;s cause. Jonathan is a type of the martyr-friend who dies alongside the anointed: &#8220;greater love has no one than this, that someone lay down his life for his friends&#8221; (John 15:13). Jonathan&#8217;s death on the high places in the battle where Saul also fell is the type of the disciples who will die in the cause of the greater David. The refrain &#8220;how the mighty have fallen&#8221; is the question that resurrection answers.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&#8220;I grieve for you, my brother Jonathan; you were so dear to me. Your love was more wonderful than the love of women.&#8221; Jonathan&#8217;s surpassing covenant love — greater than the most intimate human love — is the type of Christ&#8217;s love for his own: &#8220;having loved his own who were in the world, he loved them to the end&#8221; (John 13:1). The &#8220;more wonderful than the love of women&#8221; is not a comparison that diminishes human love but one that designates the category of the highest love possible — and declares Jonathan&#8217;s covenantal fidelity to have exceeded even that. Christ&#8217;s love surpasses in the same way: not by quantitative comparison but by ontological category — the love of the eternal Son for those he has given his life for.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&#8220;How the mighty have fallen, and the weapons of war have perished!&#8221; — the lament&#8217;s final note: total loss, nothing salvaged. The typology of resurrection is the reversal of this exact ending: what appeared to be total loss — the anointed dead, the disciples scattered, the weapons of the kingdom seemingly destroyed — becomes total gain. Paul&#8217;s &#8220;O death, where is your victory? O death, where is your sting?&#8221; (1 Cor 15:55) is the resurrection&#8217;s answer to the qinah. The lament that ends with &#8220;the weapons of war have perished&#8221; is answered by the risen Christ who says &#8220;all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me&#8221; (Matt 28:18).</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "1": "<p>David inquires of YHWH before his first post-Saul move — the anointed king&#8217;s constant orientation to the Father&#8217;s direction. Christ&#8217;s ministry is characterized by the same pattern: &#8220;the Son can do nothing of his own accord, but only what he sees the Father doing&#8221; (John 5:19); &#8220;I do nothing on my own authority, but speak just as the Father taught me&#8221; (John 8:28). The anointed king who will not move without divine consultation is the type of Christ whose entire mission is the execution of the Father&#8217;s will. The two questions — &#8220;shall I go up?&#8221; and &#8220;where?&#8221; — mirror the Son&#8217;s dependence on the Father&#8217;s specific direction, not merely general permission.</p>",
    "2": "<p>David ascends to Hebron with his two wives — the beginning of his household&#8217;s expansion at the Patriarchal city. The anointed king establishing his household at Hebron, the city of the covenant with Abraham, connects the Davidic covenant to the Abrahamic. Christ, the &#8220;seed of Abraham&#8221; (Gal 3:16) and &#8220;son of David&#8221; (Matt 1:1), fulfills both covenantal lines. The movement to Hebron is a movement to the covenantal center of the Patriarchal promises — the anointed king occupying the ground of the Abrahamic blessing that his reign will extend to the nations.</p>",
    "3": "<p>David&#8217;s men settle in the towns around Hebron — the anointed king&#8217;s community taking root in the land. The communities that gather around the anointed are the type of the church that forms around Christ: &#8220;you are no longer foreigners and strangers, but fellow citizens with God&#8217;s people and also members of his household&#8221; (Eph 2:19). The households gathering around David at Hebron are the early communities of covenant loyalty that anticipate the ecclesial gathering around the greater David. Each man with his household mirrors the household-faith of Acts (Acts 11:14; 16:31).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The men of Judah anoint David king over the house of Judah — the first stage of a two-stage anointing. Paul&#8217;s principle in Rom 1:16 (&#8220;to the Jew first and also to the Greek&#8221;) and Acts 1:8 (&#8220;Jerusalem, Judea, Samaria, and to the ends of the earth&#8221;) reflects this same pattern of covenant expansion: the covenant community first receives the king, and through them the blessing extends outward. David&#8217;s anointing at Hebron over Judah is the partial fulfillment awaiting the full anointing over all Israel — as Christ&#8217;s resurrection and ascension is the already of a kingdom not yet fully revealed at his return.</p>",
    "5": "<p>David sends to Jabesh-gilead: &#8220;May YHWH show you steadfast love and faithfulness because you showed covenant love to Saul.&#8221; The anointed king seeking out those who showed <em>ḥeseḏ</em> to the previous anointed is the type of Christ who values and responds to covenant faithfulness wherever it is found. The woman who anointed Jesus &#8220;in advance for burial&#8221; (Matt 26:12) receives similarly: &#8220;wherever this gospel is proclaimed in the whole world, what she has done will also be told in memory of her&#8221; (Matt 26:13). The anointed acknowledges and honors the <em>ḥeseḏ</em> shown to those in covenant relationship with him.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&#8220;May YHWH show you steadfast love and faithfulness; and I too will do good to you.&#8221; David aligns his own <em>ḥeseḏ</em> with YHWH&#8217;s — his covenant faithfulness is an extension of YHWH&#8217;s. Christ is the supreme instance of this alignment: &#8220;whoever has seen me has seen the Father&#8221; (John 14:9). The anointed king whose covenant faithfulness is a direct expression of YHWH&#8217;s covenant faithfulness is the pattern that Christ fulfills perfectly. The promise &#8220;I too will repay your kindness&#8221; is the type of Christ&#8217;s promise to honor those who serve the least of his brothers (Matt 25:40).</p>",
    "7": "<p>&#8220;Now let your hands be strong — Saul your lord is dead, and the house of Judah has anointed me king.&#8221; The announcement of the new king to those who mourned the old is the type of the resurrection announcement: the old order has ended, the new king is anointed. The angels at the tomb announce to the disciples — who have been mourning the dead Jesus — that he is risen and reigning (Matt 28:5-7). The call &#8220;let your hands be strong&#8221; is the resurrection empowerment: because the true anointed now reigns, the community of faith is called to courage and strength (1 Cor 15:58: &#8220;be steadfast, immovable, always abounding in the work of the Lord&#8221;).</p>",
    "8": "<p>Abner installs Ishbosheth at Mahanaim — the false king established in the Transjordanian refuge by human power. The rival to the true anointed, set up by a military strongman in a defensive location, is the anti-type of Christ&#8217;s kingdom. Rev 13:11-12: the false prophet who installs the beast, making the world worship the rival king — the Abner-Ishbosheth pattern is the OT structure of the antichrist dynamic. The rival to the true anointed can never hold the territory that belongs to the rightful king; the Mahanaim period is temporary, as all earthly kingdoms that oppose Christ are temporary.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Ishbosheth over Gilead, the Ashurites, Jezreel, Ephraim, Benjamin, and &#8220;all Israel&#8221; — the claimed territorial extent of the false king. The rival&#8217;s claim to comprehensive sovereignty is the anti-type of Christ&#8217;s actual sovereignty: &#8220;all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me&#8221; (Matt 28:18). Ishbosheth&#8217;s claim to &#8220;all Israel&#8221; is nominal; Christ&#8217;s claim is ontological. The territories claimed by the false king are the territories Christ already owns — they are not divided between two kings in reality, only in the present age&#8217;s provisional appearance.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Ishbosheth reigned two years; David at Hebron, seven and a half years. The comparative duration — two versus seven — is the type of the contrast between the reign of the world&#8217;s kings and the eternal reign of Christ. Rev 17:10 uses numbered years for the reigns of earthly kings who will give way to the Lamb; Dan 7:25 speaks of a time when the saints are given into the hand of the horn &#8220;for a time, times, and half a time.&#8221; The brevity of all rival reigns against the eternal duration of the true anointed&#8217;s kingdom is the trajectory the civil war narrates on the national scale.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Seven years and six months at Hebron — the Hebron reign as the period of partial fulfillment. Christ&#8217;s reign from the resurrection to the parousia is the &#8220;Hebron period&#8221; of partial fulfillment: already anointed, already victorious, but not yet visibly reigning over all. The &#8220;already/not yet&#8221; structure of NT eschatology — Christ already Lord of all (Acts 2:36) but all things not yet subjected to him (Heb 2:8) — is the Hebron-to-Jerusalem pattern. The full, visible, undisputed reign is coming; the present reign is real but partial in its manifestation.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Abner and Ishbosheth&#8217;s forces march to Gibeon; Joab and David&#8217;s men meet them. The two sides facing each other across the pool is the type of the spiritual conflict between the kingdom of Christ and the kingdom of the world — not yet resolved by full submission, still contested in the present age. The pool of Gibeon as contested ground reflects the NT&#8217;s description of the present age as the site of spiritual warfare (Eph 6:12: &#8220;we do not wrestle against flesh and blood, but against the rulers, against the authorities, against the cosmic powers over this present darkness&#8221;).</p>",
    "13": "<p>The two forces taking positions on opposite sides of the pool — symmetrical, face to face. The civil war that divides Israel is the type of the division within humanity that Christ comes to resolve: &#8220;Do you think that I have come to give peace on earth? No, I tell you, but rather division&#8221; (Luke 12:51) — Christ&#8217;s coming initially intensifies the conflict before its ultimate resolution. The two sides of the pool represent the two orientations of human allegiance: toward the true anointed or toward his rival. Joab&#8217;s forces are the type of the church militant engaged in the conflict of the present age.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Abner proposes champions combat — &#8220;let the young men rise and play before us.&#8221; The proposal that the political question be decided by representative combat is the structure of the incarnation: the conflict between sin/death and righteousness/life is decided by the single representative, the second Adam (1 Cor 15:22: &#8220;in Adam all die, so also in Christ shall all be made alive&#8221;). The great battle is decided by a representative whose performance determines the fate of all who are identified with him. Christ is the true champion whose single combat with sin and death at the cross resolves what no collective human effort could settle.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Twelve Benjaminites vs. twelve of David&#8217;s men — equal numbers, representative of the whole. The twelve-against-twelve format resonates with the twelve tribes of Israel and the twelve apostles of Christ&#8217;s kingdom: &#8220;you will sit on twelve thrones, judging the twelve tribes of Israel&#8221; (Matt 19:28). The representative structure of both the civil war contest and Christ&#8217;s appointment of twelve apostles reflects the same principle of covenant representation — the whole is present and determined in the few who stand for it.</p>",
    "16": "<p>All twenty-four fall together — the champions combat produces mutual destruction and no verdict. The indecisive result of human champions combat is the type of the law&#8217;s inability to resolve the conflict between sin and righteousness: &#8220;for what the law could not do, weak as it was through the flesh, God did by sending his own Son&#8221; (Rom 8:3). Every human representative combat ends in mutual death — no human champion can decisively defeat sin and death for others. Christ as the divine-human champion is the one who wins the contest without being destroyed by it — his resurrection is the decisive verdict that human champions combat could never deliver.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Abner and the men of Israel are defeated by David&#8217;s men. The gradual military victory of David&#8217;s forces over the Saulide remnant is the type of Christ&#8217;s progressive victory over his enemies: &#8220;he must reign until he has put all his enemies under his feet&#8221; (1 Cor 15:25). The defeat of Ishbosheth&#8217;s forces is not immediate but progressive — battle by battle, attrition by attrition — as the new kingdom advances. The pattern of &#8220;the war was long&#8221; but the outcome certain reflects the NT&#8217;s eschatological confidence: Christ&#8217;s kingdom will prevail even if the conflict is extended.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The three sons of Zeruiah — Joab, Abishai, Asahel — introduced as David&#8217;s fighting men. The military arm of the anointed king&#8217;s advance is staffed by those in closest kinship with him. The church as the body of Christ — those who bear his name and participate in his mission — is the type of Zeruiah&#8217;s sons: kinship-defined, covenant-loyal, fighting on behalf of the anointed&#8217;s cause. Asahel&#8217;s swiftness as a gazelle is the type of the Spirit-empowered zeal of early Christian witnesses (Acts 2:41: three thousand in one day; Acts 17:6: those who have &#8220;turned the world upside down&#8221;).</p>",
    "19": "<p>Asahel pursues Abner without deviation — a type of single-minded zeal that is both admirable and ultimately self-destructive without wisdom. The contrast with Christ is instructive: Christ is both zealous (John 2:17: zeal for the Father&#8217;s house consumes him) and infinitely wise (Col 2:3: in whom are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge). Paul&#8217;s warning in Phil 3:10-14 about pressing on toward the goal with both intensity and discernment reflects the lesson Asahel&#8217;s death illustrates. Zeal without wisdom for the anointed&#8217;s cause can destroy the zealous.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Abner recognizes Asahel and calls him by name — the pursuer is known to the one being pursued. Christ knows those who pursue him: &#8220;I know my own and my own know me&#8221; (John 10:14). The recognition of the individual by the anointed — calling by name — is the pastoral motif of Christ&#8217;s relationship with his own. Mary Magdalene is recognized and called by name at the tomb (John 20:16: &#8220;Jesus said to her, &#8216;Mary&#8217;&#8221;). Abner&#8217;s recognition of Asahel is a type of this naming-recognition, though in Abner&#8217;s case the recognition leads to warning rather than the commissioning that follows Christ&#8217;s recognition of his own.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Abner&#8217;s offer: &#8220;Turn aside and take one of the young men and seize his armor.&#8221; The offer of lesser glory — turning from the main pursuit to take secondary spoil — is the pattern of every temptation to trade the primary call for a secondary reward. Christ&#8217;s temptations in the wilderness are precisely this: the devil offers secondary goods (bread, kingdoms, spectacular rescue) in place of the primary mission of the cross (Matt 4:3-10). Asahel refuses the lesser prize; Christ refused the lesser prizes. But Asahel&#8217;s refusal leads to his death while Christ&#8217;s refusal leads to the cross and resurrection.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&#8220;Why should I strike you down? How could I face your brother Joab?&#8221; Abner&#8217;s reluctance to kill Asahel — his attempt to avoid blood guilt — is a type of every reluctant executor of judgment who knows that killing the innocent will have consequences. Pilate&#8217;s hand-washing (Matt 27:24) is the NT counterpart: &#8220;I am innocent of this man&#8217;s blood.&#8221; But unlike Pilate, who washed his hands and still condemned Christ, Abner genuinely tries to avoid the killing — his reluctance is real, not theatrical. The blood-guilt that follows anyway (Joab&#8217;s murder of Abner) is the unintended consequence of killing even in reluctant self-defense.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Asahel refuses to turn aside and Abner kills him. The death of the zealous servant in pursuit of the anointed&#8217;s enemy is the type of the martyr who dies in the cause of Christ&#8217;s kingdom. Rev 6:9-11: the souls of those slain for the word of God are under the altar, asking &#8220;how long?&#8221; — the martyrs who fell in the cause of the anointed, awaiting the day when their blood is avenged and the kingdom is fully established. Asahel fell on the road; the martyrs fall in the arena, the marketplace, the courts. Both categories of fallen servants await vindication from the anointed king.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Joab and Abishai continue the pursuit until sunset — the relentless advance of the covenant cause even after one of its servants falls. The church does not stop its mission because members are killed; the death of servants does not terminate the advance of the anointed&#8217;s cause. Acts 8:4: after Stephen&#8217;s stoning, &#8220;those who were scattered went about preaching the word.&#8221; The pursuit continues; the sunset comes but the cause does not end. Joab&#8217;s continued pursuit despite Asahel&#8217;s death is the type of the church&#8217;s continued mission despite persecution and loss.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The Benjaminites form a unit on the hill — the remnant of the old order rallying for a last stand. The regrouping of those loyal to the old covenant arrangement (Saul&#8217;s tribe, the old anointing) against the new is the type of every resistance to Christ&#8217;s advancing kingdom. The hill of Ammah is the high point of old-order resistance before the ceasefire. Paul&#8217;s description of his own pre-conversion zeal — &#8220;as to righteousness under the law, blameless&#8221; (Phil 3:6) — is the Benjaminite hilltop: zealous defense of the old order at exactly the moment when the new anointing has superseded it.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Abner calls to Joab: &#8220;Must the sword devour forever? Do you not know it will end in bitterness? How long before you stop pursuing your brothers?&#8221; The appeal to cease the civil war is the type of Christ&#8217;s reconciling mission: &#8220;he himself is our peace, who has made us both one and has broken down in his flesh the dividing wall of hostility&#8221; (Eph 2:14). The appeal to brotherhood — those on opposite sides of the conflict are &#8220;brothers&#8221; in Israel — is the type of Christ&#8217;s declaration that both Jew and Gentile are one new humanity in him. The civil war must end; the reconciling work of the anointed is the means of its ending.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Joab&#8217;s oath: &#8220;As God lives, if you had not spoken, the men would not have stopped pursuing their brothers until morning.&#8221; The ceasefire that preserves the remaining lives on both sides is the type of the intercession that restrains judgment. Christ&#8217;s high priestly intercession is the &#8220;if you had not spoken&#8221; that holds back the full execution of judgment against those who are in covenant with him. Heb 7:25: &#8220;he always lives to make intercession&#8221; — the continual &#8220;as God lives, we will not pursue them to their destruction&#8221; is the anointed&#8217;s unceasing intercessory work on behalf of his people.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The shofar ceasefire — all the men stop and no longer pursue. The signal that ends the battle and preserves the remaining lives on both sides is the type of the eschatological trumpet that will end the present age&#8217;s conflict: &#8220;the last trumpet will sound, and the dead will be raised imperishable, and we shall be changed&#8221; (1 Cor 15:52). The shofar of the ceasefire at Gibeon is a minor type of the great trumpet of the end — the signal from the anointed that changes everything and brings the long conflict to its appointed conclusion.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Abner&#8217;s forces march through the night, cross the Jordan, return to Mahanaim. The retreat to the Transjordanian refuge — the place of the old order&#8217;s last stand — is the type of every retreat from the anointed&#8217;s advancing kingdom. The Transjordan has been the territory of those who do not yet fully participate in the covenant land&#8217;s promises; Mahanaim is the eastern refuge for those who cannot hold the western territory. The old order retreats across the Jordan — as all earthly powers will ultimately withdraw before the full establishment of Christ&#8217;s kingdom.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Joab returns and counts his dead: nineteen men missing, plus Asahel. The accountability of the anointed&#8217;s commander for the lives of those under him is the type of Christ&#8217;s own accountability for his flock: &#8220;Of those whom you gave me I have lost not one&#8221; (John 18:9). The numbering of the fallen — not lost but accounted for — reflects the shepherd&#8217;s knowledge of every sheep. Christ loses none of those the Father has given him (John 6:39); the loss of nineteen plus Asahel in David&#8217;s service is mourned precisely because each life in the anointed&#8217;s service is counted and known.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Three hundred sixty of Abner&#8217;s men killed — the decisive Davidic victory. The progressive military superiority of the anointed&#8217;s forces reflects the theological principle of 2 Sam 3:1: &#8220;David grew stronger and stronger.&#8221; Paul&#8217;s proclamation that Christ&#8217;s kingdom advances until all enemies are made his footstool (1 Cor 15:25-27) is the theological articulation of the military pattern the civil war illustrates. Each battle builds toward the final decisive victory; each engagement in which the anointed&#8217;s cause prevails is a type of the eschatological triumph.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Asahel buried at Bethlehem, his father&#8217;s tomb — the martyr returned to the ancestral ground. Bethlehem as the city of David is the covenantal center; burial there is burial in the anointed&#8217;s own hometown. Christ&#8217;s own burial — in a borrowed tomb, near Jerusalem — is the greater act: the anointed himself enters the earth, making all burial ground covenantally significant. The Christian burial tradition&#8217;s insistence on the resurrection of the body reflects the theological weight that the anointed&#8217;s burial and resurrection give to every physical interment.</p>"
  },
  "3": {
    "1": "<p>&#8220;David grew stronger and stronger, the house of Saul grew weaker and weaker.&#8221; The summary statement of the civil war is the type of Christ&#8217;s progressive kingdom advance: &#8220;he must reign until he has put all his enemies under his feet&#8221; (1 Cor 15:25). The two trajectories — growing strength and growing weakness — are the pattern of the present age: Christ&#8217;s kingdom expanding, the powers of the old order declining. The process is not immediate but &#8220;long&#8221; (<em>ʾăreḵāh</em>) — as the NT&#8217;s eschatological patience acknowledges: &#8220;the Lord is not slow to fulfill his promise as some count slowness&#8221; (2 Pet 3:9).</p>",
    "2": "<p>The list of David&#8217;s sons at Hebron begins — the anointed king&#8217;s household expanding. Christ&#8217;s household — his church — also grows: &#8220;to him who sits on the throne and to the Lamb be blessing and honor and glory and might forever and ever&#8221; (Rev 5:13) is sung by the expanding multitude gathered from every nation. The sons of David born at Hebron are the type of the children of God born of the Spirit — the new-creation family that the anointed king&#8217;s reign produces. &#8220;He will see his offspring and prolong his days&#8221; (Isa 53:10) is the messianic promise that David&#8217;s Hebron sons anticipate.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Absalom son of Maacah daughter of Talmai king of Geshur — the son who will become the usurper. The inclusion of a son born to a foreign princess, who will grow up to rebel against his father, is the type of the betrayal within the household of the anointed. Judas &#8220;one of the twelve&#8221; (Matt 26:14) is the supreme NT instance of the insider-betrayer. The anointed&#8217;s household includes those who will become his enemies; Christ&#8217;s choosing of Judas was not oversight but typological fulfillment (John 13:18: &#8220;that the Scripture might be fulfilled&#8221;).</p>",
    "4": "<p>Adonijah son of Haggith — fourth in birth order, fourth in the succession line. The sons listed in birth order are the hierarchy of claim — each can only reign if those before him die or fail. The succession crisis that eventually reaches Solomon through the deaths and failures of Amnon, Absalom, and Adonijah is the OT type of the eschatological succession: only the one who is the Father&#8217;s eternal Son — not fourth in line but the only begotten — will receive the eternal kingdom. The crowding of the succession list contrasts with Christ&#8217;s uncontested sonship: &#8220;my beloved Son, in whom I am well pleased&#8221; (Matt 3:17).</p>",
    "5": "<p>Ithream by Eglah — the sixth son completes the Hebron list. Six sons from six wives at Hebron: the partial household of the Hebron period. The number six falls short of the seven of completion — as the Hebron period itself is the incomplete kingdom period before the full establishment at Jerusalem. Christ&#8217;s own family — &#8220;the church of the firstborn&#8221; (Heb 12:23) — is still being gathered; the full household is not yet complete until the last elect person is brought in. The seventh son, born at Jerusalem, would complete what Hebron began; Christ&#8217;s kingdom completion awaits the new Jerusalem (Rev 21:2).</p>",
    "6": "<p>Abner consolidating power in the house of Saul — the military strongman who is the real power behind the nominal king. The pattern of human power-brokers who use the nominal king as a vehicle for their own ambition is the type of every system that claims God&#8217;s name while serving human power. Christ&#8217;s critique of the scribes and Pharisees (Matt 23) targets precisely this pattern: those who sit in Moses&#8217;s seat (using the covenant structure) while building their own power at the people&#8217;s expense. Abner&#8217;s consolidation under the Saulide banner is the anti-type of Christ&#8217;s servant-kingship (Mark 10:45).</p>",
    "7": "<p>Ishbosheth accuses Abner of taking Saul&#8217;s concubine — the political accusation that breaks the alliance. The exposure of the contradiction between claimed loyalty and actual conduct is the type of prophetic confrontation. Nathan&#8217;s &#8220;you are the man&#8221; to David (2 Sam 12:7), Christ&#8217;s &#8220;you have heard it said... but I say to you&#8221; (Matt 5:21-48) — the prophetic word that exposes the gap between claimed covenant loyalty and actual behavior. Ishbosheth&#8217;s accusation inadvertently triggers the collapse of the old order; prophetic confrontation often catalyzes the change it announces.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Abner&#8217;s furious protest of loyalty while at the moment of betrayal — &#8220;I have been showing <em>ḥeseḏ</em> to the house of Saul&#8221; — is the type of self-justifying loyalty claims in the face of the truth. Judas&#8217;s &#8220;is it I, Rabbi?&#8221; (Matt 26:25) has the same structure: the betrayer asking the victim to confirm his innocence even as the betrayal is in process. The anointed sees through both Abner&#8217;s claim and Judas&#8217;s: &#8220;you have said so&#8221; (Matt 26:25) — the word of the anointed cuts through the self-justification with quiet, devastating precision.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Abner&#8217;s oath: &#8220;God do so to me and more if I do not carry out what YHWH has sworn to David.&#8221; The defector who swears to fulfill the divine covenant promise he previously opposed is a type of Christ as the guarantor of the covenant: &#8220;all the promises of God find their Yes in him&#8221; (2 Cor 1:20). What Abner only promises under the pressure of political defeat, Christ fulfills through voluntary covenant obedience. The oath invokes YHWH&#8217;s own sworn word as the standard — as Christ&#8217;s obedience fulfills the Father&#8217;s sworn promises (Luke 1:72-73: &#8220;to show the mercy promised to our fathers and to remember his holy covenant, the oath that he swore to our father Abraham&#8221;).</p>",
    "10": "<p>&#8220;To transfer the kingdom from the house of Saul and establish the throne of David from Dan to Beersheba.&#8221; The transfer of the kingdom from the provisional anointing to the enduring anointing is the type of the transfer from the Mosaic covenant (provisional, conditioned on Israel&#8217;s performance) to the Davidic/new covenant (unconditional, guaranteed by YHWH&#8217;s own oath). Heb 7:18-19: &#8220;the former commandment is set aside because of its weakness and uselessness... a better hope is introduced.&#8221; The political transfer Abner promises is the type of the covenantal transfer Christ accomplishes.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Ishbosheth cannot answer Abner because he fears him — the nominal king speechless before the actual power. The false king&#8217;s silence before the challenge is the type of every earthly power that has no answer when confronted with the claims of Christ&#8217;s kingdom. At the last day, &#8220;every mouth will be stopped&#8221; (Rom 3:19) — the same silence that Ishbosheth experiences before Abner will characterize every rival to Christ before the judgment seat. The false king has nothing to say because he has no true authority; Christ alone speaks with divine authority (Matt 7:29).</p>",
    "12": "<p>Abner negotiates directly with David: &#8220;whose is the land? Make a treaty with me.&#8221; The recognition that the land belongs to the rightful anointed — even by his former opponents — is the type of the eschatological confession: &#8220;every knee will bow and every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is Lord&#8221; (Phil 2:10-11). Abner&#8217;s question &#8220;whose is the land?&#8221; is the question that all creation will ultimately answer correctly — it belongs to Christ, the one to whom all authority has been given (Matt 28:18). The treaty offer is the voluntary submission of those who had previously resisted the anointed&#8217;s claim.</p>",
    "13": "<p>David&#8217;s condition: &#8220;Bring me Michal.&#8221; Before David will seal the treaty, he requires the return of his bride. The anointed king&#8217;s insistence on the return of his bride before extending covenant peace is the type of Christ&#8217;s claim on his church: &#8220;Christ loved the church and gave himself up for her, that he might sanctify her&#8221; (Eph 5:25-26). The church is Christ&#8217;s bride — claimed at the price of his own life, returned to him through the new covenant. David&#8217;s condition &#8220;first bring my wife Michal&#8221; is the anointed king&#8217;s declaration that he will not extend his covenant without reclaiming what belongs to him.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The legal claim for Michal: &#8220;I paid the bride-price of a hundred Philistine foreskins.&#8221; David&#8217;s claim on Michal rests on a price already paid — an extraordinary and violent bride-price that established irrevocable legal ownership. Christ&#8217;s claim on his church rests on a price already paid: &#8220;you were bought with a price&#8221; (1 Cor 6:20); &#8220;you were ransomed... with the precious blood of Christ&#8221; (1 Pet 1:18-19). The bride-price paid establishes the claim permanently — neither Phaltiel&#8217;s years with Michal nor the world&#8217;s hold on the redeemed can override the price already paid by the true anointed.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Ishbosheth sends for Michal and takes her from Phaltiel — the political machinery reclaiming the bride for her rightful husband. The instruments of the old order (Ishbosheth) are used to return what belongs to the new anointed — a type of how the old covenant structures functioned to prepare for and deliver Christ&#8217;s bride. Paul&#8217;s argument in Galatians: the law was &#8220;a guardian until Christ came&#8221; (Gal 3:24) — the old covenant served Christ&#8217;s purposes even as it prepared for its own supersession. The returning of Michal by the old-order king is the type of the law serving the gospel&#8217;s purposes.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Phaltiel follows Michal weeping until Abner turns him back. The grief of the one who must release what belongs to another is the type of the world&#8217;s loss when Christ claims his own. The &#8220;weeping and gnashing of teeth&#8221; (Matt 8:12; 22:13) that characterizes those excluded from the kingdom wedding banquet — the grief of those who held something that was not truly theirs. Phaltiel&#8217;s weeping is not condemned but acknowledged — the human cost of the anointed&#8217;s reclamation of his bride. The single word from Abner — &#8220;go back&#8221; — is the line that no human grief can cross when the anointed calls his own.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Abner&#8217;s report to the elders: &#8220;For some time you have been seeking David as your king.&#8221; The acknowledgment that the desire for the true anointed was already present among the people, suppressed by the old order, is the type of the Spirit&#8217;s preparatory work: &#8220;No one can come to me unless the Father who sent me draws him&#8221; (John 6:44). The elders who wanted David but had not yet declared it are the type of those in whom the Spirit has worked recognition before the open confession is made. Abner&#8217;s political insight mirrors the theological reality: the move to the true king was desired before it was enacted.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The divine oracle Abner cites: &#8220;By my servant David&#8217;s hand I will save my people Israel from the hand of all their enemies.&#8221; The title &#8220;my servant David&#8221; (<em>ʿaḇdî dāwid</em>) is the royal election formula that anticipates the Servant Songs of Isaiah: &#8220;Behold my servant, whom I uphold, my chosen, in whom my soul delights&#8221; (Isa 42:1). Christ is addressed at his baptism with precisely this formula (Matt 3:17: &#8220;this is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased&#8221;) — the divine identification of the anointed as servant, savior, and elect. The salvation from all enemies that David&#8217;s servant role promises Christ fulfills eschatologically.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Abner speaks separately to the Benjaminites — the tribe with the most reason to resist the Davidic transition, Saul&#8217;s own tribe. The specific outreach to those with the deepest investment in the old order is the type of Paul&#8217;s mission strategy: &#8220;to the Jews first and also to the Greek&#8221; (Rom 1:16) — and specifically to the most resistant, the Pharisee Saul of Tarsus becoming Paul. Benjamin&#8217;s resistance is not absolute; even those most invested in the old covenant arrangement can be brought to recognize the new anointed. The Benjamin-first approach is Abner&#8217;s political wisdom and Paul&#8217;s missionary pattern.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Abner comes to David with twenty men; David makes a feast. The covenant-ratification feast — sharing table with the former enemy&#8217;s general — is the type of the eschatological banquet: &#8220;people will come from east and west, and from north and south, and recline at table in the kingdom of God&#8221; (Luke 13:29). The feast Christ holds for those who come from the surrounding territories — former rivals and enemies, now welcomed to the covenant table — is the messianic fulfillment of David&#8217;s feast at Hebron. Those who were against the anointed and then come to him are welcomed with a table, not a sword.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Abner&#8217;s promise: &#8220;I will gather all Israel to you so that they may make a covenant with you and you may reign over all that your soul desires.&#8221; The gathering of all Israel to the anointed through covenant is the type of the eschatological gathering Christ promises: &#8220;I, when I am lifted up from the earth, will draw all people to myself&#8221; (John 12:32). Abner&#8217;s promise to deliver all Israel to David is the human type; Christ&#8217;s own redemptive work is the divine fulfillment. The &#8220;all that your soul desires&#8221; finds its ultimate answer in Ps 2:8: &#8220;ask of me, and I will make the nations your heritage, and the ends of the earth your possession.&#8221;</p>",
    "22": "<p>Joab returns from a raid with plunder just as Abner has left. The timing — the military commander arriving after the king&#8217;s covenant meeting — is the narrative setup for the interruption of covenant peace by kinship-violence. The conflict between the anointed&#8217;s covenant purposes and his closest followers&#8217; personal agendas runs through the NT as well: Peter rebuking Jesus (Matt 16:22), James and John requesting first seats (Mark 10:37), the disciples arguing about greatness (Luke 22:24). The anointed king&#8217;s nearest followers repeatedly act in ways that contradict his mission.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Joab is told: Abner came to the king and was sent away in peace. The information that the king has made peace with the former enemy — without consulting the chief of staff — is the type of the disciples learning that Christ has extended grace beyond what they expected. Peter&#8217;s surprise at Gentile inclusion (Acts 10:34-35), the elder brother&#8217;s anger at the prodigal&#8217;s reception (Luke 15:28-30) — the anointed&#8217;s peace-extensions consistently exceed and sometimes violate the expectations of those closest to him. Joab&#8217;s reaction to the peace-sending will be the response of those who want judgment, not mercy.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Joab challenges David: &#8220;What have you done?&#8221; — the same accusatory question Abner used to Joab in v. 26. The circular accusation: Abner accused Joab of pursuing without end, now Joab accuses David of making peace without calculation. The anointed king is accused from both sides — the one pursuing blood revenge accuses him of excessive peace; the one being pursued accused him of excessive warfare. Christ&#8217;s judgment by both the Pharisees (too lax with sinners) and the people (too strict in his demands) is the pattern: &#8220;for John came neither eating nor drinking, and they say, &#8216;he has a demon&#8217;; the Son of Man came eating and drinking, and they say, &#8216;look at him&#8217;&#8221; (Matt 11:18-19).</p>",
    "25": "<p>Joab&#8217;s accusation: &#8220;Abner came to deceive you, to spy out your movements.&#8221; The charge that the king has been naive or deceived in extending peace is the type of worldly wisdom&#8217;s accusation against grace. The anointed&#8217;s extension of covenant peace to former enemies looks like naivety to those who operate by the logic of blood-revenge and power politics. Christ&#8217;s command to &#8220;love your enemies&#8221; (Matt 5:44) consistently receives the Joab-objection: it is naive, it will be exploited, it shows weakness. The anointed king&#8217;s peace-making is not naivety but a higher wisdom that the Joab-perspective cannot access.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Joab sends for Abner without David&#8217;s knowledge and brings him back. The circumventing of the anointed king&#8217;s decision — acting behind his back — is the type of every betrayal of Christ&#8217;s purposes by those who claim his name. Judas&#8217;s secret arrangement with the chief priests (Matt 26:14-16) is the NT instance of the Joab pattern: a close follower of the anointed taking independent action against the anointed&#8217;s expressed purposes. &#8220;David did not know&#8221; — as Christ did not commission Judas&#8217;s betrayal — the crime of the anointed&#8217;s closest servant is committed independently of the anointed&#8217;s will.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Joab stabs Abner at the gate — blood revenge in the place of covenant justice. The murder at the city gate — the legal space where justice was administered — is the type of the corruption of the justice system to destroy the anointed&#8217;s purposes. The gate where justice should be rendered becomes the site of treachery; the hall where Christ should have received a fair trial (before Pilate who &#8220;found no guilt in him&#8221;, John 18:38) becomes the site of his condemnation. The killing of Abner &#8220;because of the blood of Asahel his brother&#8221; is the human vendetta that overrides covenant peace — as personal agendas override justice in the passion narrative.</p>",
    "28": "<p>David declares: &#8220;I and my kingdom are forever innocent before YHWH of the blood of Abner son of Ner.&#8221; The anointed king&#8217;s declaration of innocence from the blood of the one his servant killed is the type of Christ&#8217;s complete righteousness even when those acting in his name do evil. Christ is not implicated in every act done &#8220;in his name&#8221; — the blood of those killed by the Crusades, the Inquisition, Christian nationalism does not attach to Christ. The declaration &#8220;I am innocent of this blood&#8221; (Matt 27:24, Pilate) is tragically ironic when Pilate says it; it is completely true when David says it, and supremely true of Christ.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The curse on Joab&#8217;s house: disease, disability, violent death, poverty. The transgenerational consequence of the blood-guilt — &#8220;let it fall on Joab&#8217;s head and on all his father&#8217;s house&#8221; — is the type of the blood-guilt that returns on those who shed innocent blood. Christ&#8217;s warning to Jerusalem: &#8220;so that on you may come all the righteous blood shed on earth&#8221; (Matt 23:35) — the accumulated blood-guilt of those who killed YHWH&#8217;s servants falls on the generation that rejects the Son. The curse David pronounces on Joab&#8217;s house is the type of the blood-guilt that the rejection of Christ accumulates and releases in judgment.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The narrator&#8217;s explanation: Joab and Abishai killed Abner because of Asahel&#8217;s death. The blood-revenge motive — entirely understandable within the kinship-honor code — is the OT type of the lex talionis that the cross transcends. Christ absorbs the blood-debt in himself rather than passing it on: &#8220;Father, forgive them, for they do not know what they are doing&#8221; (Luke 23:34). The blood-revenge cycle — Abner killed Asahel → Joab killed Abner → Solomon killed Joab (1 Kgs 2:34) — is the type of the sin-death cycle that Christ breaks by being the final blood-debt absorber. He does not pass the guilt on; he bears it.</p>",
    "31": "<p>David commands public mourning for Abner — the king himself walks behind the bier. The anointed king humbling himself to walk behind the bier of a former enemy is the type of Christ&#8217;s kenotic self-lowering: &#8220;taking the form of a servant, being born in the likeness of men; and being found in human form, he humbled himself&#8221; (Phil 2:7-8). The king who walks behind rather than leading the procession, who mourns the enemy-become-ally, who performs grief publicly for political and covenant purposes — this is the servant-king who subordinates his own status to the demands of covenant faithfulness.</p>",
    "32": "<p>David weeps aloud at Abner&#8217;s grave; all the people weep with him. The communal weeping led by the anointed king is the type of the eschatological mourning at the revelation of Christ: &#8220;every eye will see him, even those who pierced him, and all tribes of the earth will wail on account of him&#8221; (Rev 1:7). The mourning at the grave of the one lost to treachery — weeping over what might have been had the covenant peace been honored — is the type of the tears of those who recognize too late what the anointed&#8217;s death means. But David&#8217;s weeping is also the weeping of the faithful: the anointed who mourns genuinely for the fallen.</p>",
    "33": "<p>David&#8217;s lament: &#8220;Should Abner have died as a fool dies?&#8221; The question over the unnecessary death — the death that need not have happened if covenant peace had been honored — is the type of the lament over all unnecessary death in a world that rejects the anointed&#8217;s offer of peace. Christ weeps over Jerusalem: &#8220;Would that you, even you, had known on this day the things that make for peace!&#8221; (Luke 19:42) — the lament over the death that need not have happened, the destruction that could have been prevented if the covenant peace had been received. David&#8217;s lament over Abner is the type of Christ&#8217;s lament over Jerusalem.</p>",
    "34": "<p>&#8220;Your hands were not bound; your feet were not in fetters. You fell as one falls before the sons of wickedness.&#8221; The honorable man brought down by treachery is the type of Christ&#8217;s own death: &#8220;he was oppressed and he was afflicted, yet he opened not his mouth&#8221; (Isa 53:7) — the one whose hands were not bound by guilt, whose feet were not in the fetters of sin, who fell before the sons of wickedness. The lament that Abner died without honor, victim of betrayal, is the type of the lament over Christ crucified. But where Abner&#8217;s death is purely loss, Christ&#8217;s &#8220;fall before the sons of wickedness&#8221; is the redemptive act that purchases the lives of the sons of wickedness themselves.</p>",
    "35": "<p>David refuses to eat until sunset — public fasting as covenant mourning. The voluntary deprivation of the anointed — refusing bread on the day of the covenant ally&#8217;s burial — is the type of Christ&#8217;s fasting in the wilderness (Matt 4:2) and his statement at the Last Supper: &#8220;I will not drink again of this fruit of the vine until that day when I drink it new with you in my Father&#8217;s kingdom&#8221; (Matt 26:29). The anointed&#8217;s voluntary fasting expresses covenant solidarity with the mourning community and anticipates the eschatological feast that will end all fasting.</p>",
    "36": "<p>All the people noticed and it pleased them — everything the king did pleased all the people. The universal approval of the anointed&#8217;s conduct is a type of the eschatological vindication of Christ&#8217;s character and purposes. At the judgment, every knee will bow and every tongue confess (Phil 2:10-11) — what is now contested (Christ&#8217;s lordship, his righteousness, his purposes) will be universally recognized as just and good. The people&#8217;s approval of David&#8217;s mourning-conduct is a penultimate type of the final universal approval of the greater anointed&#8217;s conduct throughout history.</p>",
    "37": "<p>&#8220;All the people and all Israel understood that day that it was not the king&#8217;s will to kill Abner.&#8221; The public vindication of the anointed king — the people&#8217;s recognition that he acted with justice and was not responsible for the treachery of his servant — is the type of the eschatological vindication of Christ. The cross appeared to be God&#8217;s abandonment of Jesus; the resurrection is the public vindication: &#8220;God has made him both Lord and Christ, this Jesus whom you crucified&#8221; (Acts 2:36). The anointed who appeared to be complicit in every failure of justice is fully exonerated when the truth is known.</p>",
    "38": "<p>&#8220;Do you not know that a commander and a great man has fallen in Israel today?&#8221; The recognition of greatness lost — the anointed king insisting on the honor of the fallen — is the type of Christ&#8217;s honor for those who serve his cause. &#8220;Whoever would be great among you must be your servant&#8221; (Matt 20:26) — the anointed&#8217;s definition of greatness is service, and he honors the great servants who fall in his cause. Hebrews 11 is David&#8217;s lament for the anointed&#8217;s great fallen servants writ large: a catalog of those who died in faith, whose greatness the anointed acknowledges and whose vindication he will accomplish at the resurrection.</p>",
    "39": "<p>&#8220;I am weak today, though anointed king; these men, the sons of Zeruiah, are too strong for me. May YHWH repay the evildoer according to his wickedness.&#8221; David&#8217;s declaration of kenotic weakness — acknowledging that he cannot immediately execute justice against Joab — is the type of Christ&#8217;s kenosis (Phil 2:7: &#8220;emptying himself, taking the form of a servant&#8221;) and his entrusting of judgment to the Father (1 Pet 2:23: &#8220;he entrusted himself to him who judges justly&#8221;). The anointed who could exercise divine power but chooses not to, who commits the execution of justice to YHWH rather than taking it immediately — this is the cross&#8217;s logic. The weakness of the anointed is the strength of his covenant faithfulness.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('christ', '2samuel')
    merge_comm(c, CHRIST)
    save_comm('christ', '2samuel', c)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in CHRIST.values())
    print(f'2samuel mkt-christ: wrote {total} verses across ch 1-3')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
